<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Speaking at the briefing, Bra Hugh’s son Sal Masekela said the Masekela family has been overwhelmed by the kind support and messages from different people around the world. “We have been blown with the comforting messages from people who worked knew my father through his music."My father’s music touched many people and changed the lives of many souls,” he said.He said the family thanked the department of Arts and Culture for the support they have given the family since Bra Hugh died on Tuesday. Sal said since his father was loved by the many in the country and other nations abroad, there are three memorial services arranged to give the public a chance to share their memories with the legend in their lives.He said the first public memorial service would be held at the Hugh Masekela Heritage Park. At this venue, the Heritage Park will feature visuals, footage and audio that reflect Masekela’s rich and inspiring life journey.The service will take place at the Zoo Lake in Parkview between today Friday (26 January) until Thursday (1 February) - from 10:00 in the morning to 18:00 in the evening daily.The second service will take place in Gomora, Alexandra, north of Joburg.“A commemoration of Masekela’s life to be hosted in Alexandra Township where his music journey begun. The event will take place on Friday (26 January). Friends, artistic community and family will come down at the San Kopano community centre to share their memories with the man they loved in the music industry.Sal said the final tribute to his father will take place on Sunday 28 January the University of Johannesburg Soweto Campus where it will be a musical service. The day will see many artists he collaborated with performing on the day from midday.Lesetja Masilela said the three memorials will give time for the people he loved to reflect and share their memories with the legend.He stressed that the funeral will be private as Bra Hugh wished when he was alive.Masekela’s doctor Yastira Ramdas said bra Hugh was a strong man and a fighter. “His message was simple - to encourage men to get tested and treated."